observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:

Require the MA to coordinate with the Municipal Engineer (ME) and reconcile records of prior years’ completed projects that are still listed in the CIP account;

Direct the MA to obtain Certificates of Completion and Certificates of Turnover and Acceptance from the ME for completed projects, to facilitate reclassifying CIP accounts to the appropriate PPE account;

Require the MA to record the corresponding depreciation expenses for the completed projects from the date of completion until December 31, 2023, and prepare any necessary adjusting entries to reflect the correct balance of the affected PPE accounts.; and

Instruct the MA to prepare the necessary adjusting entries to correct any misstatements of the CIP accounts and related accounts, ensuring the fair presentation of these accounts in the Financial Statements (FS).

We reiterated our recommendations that the:

LCE direct the Local Finance Committee analyze the trend in collection of tax revenues and determine the amount of income that will likely be collected and use the data as inputs or benchmark in the preparation of the Annual Budget for the ensuing year;

Municipal Budget Officer, MA, and the Municipal Treasurer (MT) exercise diligence, prudence, and proper control in disposition of the MGM's funds and limit expenditures within the total income realized and collected during the year to avoid cash deficiency;

LCE require the MA and MT to prepare the Cash Analysis Report monthly to monitor the cash position of the MGM and submit this to her and all concerned offices/departments to serve as a parameter in settling obligations and ensure the stability of the MGM's financial resources; and

The MT should ensure there is sufficient cash backing for specific programs, projects and activities (PPAs) before signing any Purchase Requests.

Likewise, we recommended that the LCE direct the MT to strictly monitor the remittance of collections.

We recommended that Management:

Review the status of the non-moving balances of the Due to NGAs accounts by confirming the same to the SAs;

Make representations to the SAs to obtain authority to utilize the unexpended balances for purposes other than what is provided in the MOA.  Otherwise, return immediately the excess funds amounting to ₱442,354.11 or balances pertaining to the completed projects or activities financed by the other agencies.

We recommended that the LCE: Require the Human Resource Management Officer – Designate to assess the existing Organizational Structure, expedite filling up the vacant positions thru advertisement and assessment of qualified employees for promotion, and submit a report thereon to the LCE for approval by appropriate bodies;

Make written policy/guidelines to address the issue on the necessity and propriety of hiring JO/COS workers, who should not perform tasks assigned to existing permanent and regular employees per their job descriptions;

Limit the hiring/deployment to those offices that are extremely in need of their services; and

Prepare an evaluation report on the performance of JO/COS workers as basis for rehiring/renewal of contract.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Direct the IC to conduct a complete and timely physical count of all PPE, ensuring that all assets are physically verified, properly tagged, and documented using the prescribed RPCPPE format;
Ensure regular reconciliation between the records of the MAO (GL, PPELCs, PPE Lapsing Schedule) and the RPCPPE submitted by the IC.  Any identified discrepancies should be properly investigated, adjusted, and documented with supporting evidence;
Require the Supply and Property Unit to completely maintain and regularly update the PCs for each class of PPE, in accordance with Section 45 of the MNGAS, ensuring that all required information such as acquisition date, complete description, quantity, location, and amount are properly recorded;
Instruct the MA to ensure that the PPELCs and PPE Lapsing Schedule are fully maintained and synchronized with the balances in the GL, with complete and accurate details for each property;
Mandate the use of standardized formats prescribed by COA Circular No. 2020-006 across all PPE-related documents (e.g., RPCPPE, PCs, PPELC, PPE Lapsing Schedule) and see to it that all required fields (e.g., property number, AO, condition, etc.) are properly filled out;
Provide appropriate training and capacity building for the designated MGSO, Property Custodian, and MAO Staff on asset management and property documentation procedures to address gaps in technical knowledge and improve compliance with accounting and inventory standards;
Assign additional personnel or support staff where necessary to assist in the regular updating, monitoring, and reconciliation of property records, especially in high-volume departments or offices with significant assets; and
Establish internal controls and monitoring mechanisms to oversee the periodic reconciliation of accounting and inventory records, ensure compliance with COA requirements, and maintain transparency and accountability in asset management.

We recommended and Management agreed to require the:
MAO to –
Maintain complete and updated CIP Ledger Cards for all on-going and completed projects to ensure traceability and accuracy of reported balances;
Ensure that all adjustments, such as fund transfers (e.g., ELCAC-related), are supported with detailed documentation specifying the nature, project coverage, and justification;
Do not record unimplemented projects in the books to avoid overstating assets and liabilities;
Coordinate regularly with the Municipal Engineer’s Office (MEO) to identify completed projects and initiate timely reclassification from CIP to PPE accounts; and
Reconcile CIP balances regularly with the MEO to confirm legitimacy and completeness.
MEO to –
Prepare and submit detailed breakdowns of project costs and status for lump-sum CIP balances to support validation and reporting accuracy;
Provide the MAO with completion reports or certifications for finished projects to facilitate reclassification from CIP to PPE; and
Confirm with contractors the status of long-outstanding or delayed projects and recommend appropriate actions for updating records or initiating termination, if necessary.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Require the MT to conduct a thorough reconciliation of the CRAAF balances against the actual physical inventory of issued, unissued, and used AFs, and correct all discrepancies to establish accurate and reliable records;
Direct the AOs to present all unissued AFs as reflected in the RCD and the RAAF, and ensure that the physical balance tallies with the quantity shown on the second page of both reports;
Direct the MT to ensure that the quantity balance appearing in the CRAAF is fully supported by the actual unissued physical balance, maintaining consistency across all official records; and
Instruct the MT to implement stricter controls over the requisition, issuance, and recording of AFs, ensuring that only the quantities reasonably needed for immediate operations are requested and issued, to avoid excessive stocks at the hands of the AOs.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation and Management agreed to:
Direct the LFC to analyze trends in tax revenue collections, determine realistic income projections and use these as benchmarks in preparing the annual budget for the ensuing year in accordance with Section 316 of RA No. 7160;
Instruct the MBO, the MA, and the MT to exercise diligence, prudence, and proper control in the disposition of the MGM’s funds and ensure that expenditures do not exceed the total income actually realized and collected during the year, as mandated by Section 337 of RA No. 7160, to prevent cash deficiencies;
Require the MA and MT to jointly prepare a monthly Cash Analysis Report to monitor the MGM’s cash position to be submitted to the LCE and all concerned offices/departments, serving as a vital reference for settling obligations and ensuring the stability of the MGM’s financial resources, consistent with Section 316 of RA No. 7160; and
Mandate the MT to verify the availability of sufficient cash backing for specific PPAs before approving or signing any Purchase Requests, in compliance with Section 337 of RA No. 7160.
Likewise, we recommended and Management agreed to direct the MT to strictly monitor the remittance of collections to ensure timely and complete cash inflows, preventing delays that could worsen cash deficits.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Instruct the MAO to complete the reconciliation of the FS and SL balances of the Accounts Payable and Due to Officers and Employees accounts and ensure accurate monthly updates thereafter;
Coordinate with the MT and the MBO to prepare a payment schedule that prioritizes obligations related to basic services and essential support to constituents, such as those for JO workers, scholars, and indigents;
Prepare a regular aging schedule of payables and review it monthly to identify obligations that are overdue and require immediate action;
Continue to explore ways to improve cash inflows, including timely collection of receivables and optimizing available internal revenue sources, to support payment commitments; and
Instruct the MA to ensure that all supporting documents are properly attached at the time the payable is recognized in the books to guarantee validity of the transactions.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Prioritize the allocation of funds for loan amortization and arrearages in the Annual Investment Plan and Local Budget to ensure timely settlement of obligations to the LBP;
Include a separate budget line item for arrears and interest payments in the annual budget to gradually address the accumulated unpaid obligations;
Coordinate with the LBP to request a restructuring or revised payment schedule, if applicable, to ease the financial burden and avoid further penalties;
Strengthen cash flow planning and forecasting to ensure that sufficient funds are available to meet debt service requirements while balancing other priority programs;
Review and evaluate on-going programs and projects to identify possible areas where savings can be reallocated toward loan repayments without compromising essential services; and
Explore other revenue-generating initiatives or cost-saving measures to improve the Municipality’s financial position and build fiscal resilience.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Direct the MDRRMO to prepare the LDRRMFIP in accordance with Items 5.1.2 and 5.1.15 of COA Circular No. 2012-002 in order to come up with a complete and comprehensive plan that will serve as basis in the implementation of the MGM’s DRRM PPAs;
Direct the concerned offices to prepare and maintain complete and updated records on LDRRMF and to conduct periodic reconciliation of records to avoid discrepancies and to come up with accurate and reliable reports and records crucial for their intended users;
Direct the MBO to stop the practice of incurring obligations without cash back-up in order to avoid bloating the utilization of LDRRMF and to ensure the prompt payment of the MGM’s obligations;
Ensure that the MGM realizes its target collections within the specified period and that municipal funds are applied in accordance with law or ordinance to the payment of expenses and settlement of obligations of the municipality;
Direct the MDRRMO, MBO and the MAO to monitor closely the utilization and implementation of all PPAs under the LDRRMF to facilitate the timely reprogramming and reallocation of the fund for its optimum utilization; and
Enjoin the MDRRMO to exert more effort in implementing actions and measures pertaining to all aspects of DRRM towards building a disaster-resilient LGU and communities.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Direct the MGSO to establish a dedicated stockroom facility to properly receive, store, and control supplies and inventory items upon delivery, ensuring centralized custody before issuance to end-user offices;
Require the MGSO to strictly implement the Perpetual Inventory Method by recording all purchases as inventory upon receipt and maintaining accurate Stock Cards reflecting supplies on hand and issuance based on RIS;
Mandate the MAO to record all purchases as inventory upon receipt and to recognize expenses only upon actual consumption, ensuring compliance with MNGAS for LGUs inventory accounting procedures;
Instruct the MAO to promptly update ledger entries and prepare JEVs based on the AIR and supporting documents;
Require the MGSO to prepare and submit the SSMI regularly, consolidating all RIS to support accurate expense recognition and internal control;
Ensure both the GSO and MAO conduct and document periodic physical inventories semi-annually for supplies and annually for property and equipment, reconciling results with accounting records as mandated by Section 124; and
Provide training to GSO and MAO personnel on inventory and accounting procedures to improve compliance and internal control effectiveness.

We recommended and the Matnog Municipal School Board (MMSB) agreed to consider the following measures to strengthen its SEF planning and budgeting processes:
Follow strictly the prescribed timeline in the preparation of the annual SEF Budget as provided in DepEd-DBM-DILG JC No. 1, s. 2017;
Require the LSB to prepare the LSB three-year program, supported by approved individual SIPs and other information from DepEd Regional Office, prior to the preparation and approval of the SEF Budget and furnish the AT for reference and review purposes;
Support the SEF budget with plan of intended priority PPAs to be funded out of the fund presented by allotment class and per school; and
Require the MT, LSB and the MBO to coordinate properly so that accurate figures are included in the SEF Budget computation.
Furthermore, we recommended and the MMSB agreed, that in declaring supplemental appropriations for the SEF annual budget, to consider the actual cash availability, including not only the unexpended expenditures but also the excess of actual income over the projected amount.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive (LCE):

Prior to the conduct of the physical count, require the Municipal General Services Office (MGSO) and the Municipal Accountant’s Office (MAO) to prioritize the reconciliation process and ensure that discrepancies noted are immediately investigated and adjusted in the books accordingly;

Direct the MGSO to ensure the submission of the RPCPPE on schedule and include the names and signatures of Inventory Committee Members on the Report;

Require the Property Officer to attach stickers on each identified PPE item;

Direct the Municipal Accountant (MA) to apply the five percent salvage value rate in the computation for depreciation expense; and

Require the MAO to maintain complete and updated PPELCs to support GL account balances and the MGSO to keep corresponding PCs for control purposes.

We also recommended that Management avail of the one-time cleansing of PPE account balances pursuant to COA Circular No. 2020-006 in order to establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition, and accountability.

We strongly recommended that the LCE take the following actions:

Immediately issue a formal demand letter to all Accountable Officers in the MTO, mandating the presentation of unissued AF to the Office of the Municipal Mayor, stressing the legal implications of non-compliance, establishing a deadline for action, and delineating clear consequences for refusal to comply with the demand;

Provide the Audit Team (AT) with a copy of the list of the presented unissued AF;

Require the MT to conduct a thorough revision of the CRAAF for the period from January 2023 to December 2023. Ensure that these reports are accurate and reconciled with the physical balance of AF;

Require the MT to stop the practice of issuing new AFs if previous ones have not yet been issued/reported; and

Moving forward, require the MT to mandate all collectors to submit monthly RAAF to the MTO.

We recommended that Management:

Demand from the concerned AOs the immediate submission of liquidation documents and/or refund of the CAs if not yet utilized, otherwise, institute appropriate criminal or administrative sanctions for the continued non-compliance with the existing laws, rules and regulations on the granting, utilization and liquidation of CAs, if warranted;

Stop the practice of granting additional CAs to AOs with unliquidated CAs and transferring CAs from one AO to another in accordance with Sections 89 and 4.1.6 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular 97-002, respectively;

Provide and increase the bonding requirements of unbonded AOs and with insufficient bond, respectively, pursuant to Treasury Circular No. 02-2009 to protect the interest of the MGM, otherwise ensure that CA granted is within the limit of the fidelity bond;

Designate an SDO within the MSWDO and provide the necessary bonding requirements to facilitate the granting and liquidation of CAs intended for AICS; and

Stop the practice of stamp-signing the PCVs and authorize the Municipal Administrator through an executive order to sign for and in behalf of the Municipal Mayor for regular operating expenditures of the Municipality or adopt the guidelines set forth in COA Circular No. 2021-006 on the use of electronic documents, electronic signatures, and digital signatures in government transactions.

Likewise, we recommended that the MA ensure the completeness of documents attached to the Disbursement Vouchers (DV) prior to submission to COA to avoid suspensions or disallowances in audit.

We recommended that the LCE instruct the MA to: 

Prepare the necessary journal entries to correct the erroneous classification of accounts to reflect the correct balance of Accounts Payable in the FS;

Ensure that all financial transactions of the Municipality are properly recorded in the books pursuant to COA Circular No. 2015-009;

Verify the validity of the payables aged two years and more which remained outstanding without valid claims. Otherwise, cause the reversion thereof to the unappropriated surplus of the GF; and

Henceforth, strictly comply with Section 98 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 76-45 on reversion of long outstanding payables.

We recommended that the LCE take the following actions:

Require the MA to provide justification for why liquidated damages were not deducted from the contractor's claim;

Instruct the ME to submit inspection reports indicating the completion percentage at the end of the completion period for both projects;

Based on the reports submitted by the ME, direct the MA to compute the actual liquidated damages, if applicable, and deduct them from the remaining claim of the contractor. If the claim is less than the computed damages, issue a demand letter to the contractor to refund the excess claim; and

Instruct the ME to closely monitor the implementation of projects to derive the optimum benefits therefrom.

We recommended that Management require the:

MA to conduct detailed review and analysis of the Inter-Agency Payables accounts, including confirmation and reconciliation with the concerned government agencies to come up with the correct unremitted balances of the payable accounts.  Thereafter, prepare the necessary adjusting entry, if warranted;

MA to monitor closely the preparation of necessary schedules of remittances of withheld amounts and ensure that these are paid in full within the prescribed deadlines;

MT and MA to ensure availability of funds for the immediate remittance of the mandatory contributions and loan amortizations to GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth to avoid paying penalties, surcharges and interest arising from delayed remittances; and

Require the liable/accountable officials to settle personally the interest due to GSIS and future penalties and surcharges if determined negligent in the performance of duties.

We reiterated our previous year’s recommendation that the LCE direct the LDRRM Council to: 

Monitor properly the utilization of the LDRRMF by ensuring the efficient and effective implementation of PPAs to promote a more disaster-resilient community and help reduce disaster risks;

Use the unexpended balances of the LDRRMF by incorporating these in the LDRRMFIP and submit the same, including supplemental Investment Programs, if any, to the AT within the prescribed period; 

Ensure that unobligated balances of PPAs for capital outlay were made part of the continuing appropriations in the GF books; and

Include only eligible PPAs in the LDRRMFIP.

We recommended that Management:

Require all of the accountable officers (AOs) who have unremitted and undeposited collections to deposit the same to the depository account of the Municipality;

Resort to all administrative and other legal remedies inorder to collect those unremitted/undeposited collections.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Fast-track or expedite the restructuring of its Inventory Committee and designate immediately a qualified MGSO who will be in charge of the safekeeping of MGM’s physical assets and related records;
Instruct the Inventory Committee to undertake physical inventory of all the PPE items to determine their existence, location, condition and other relevant information, and prepare immediately the corresponding RPCPPE;
Direct the MA and the Municipal Treasurer (MT) to prepare and maintain complete and updated PPELCs and PCs, respectively;
Require the MAO and MTO to prioritize the reconciliation process and ensure that discrepancies noted are immediately investigated and adjusted accordingly in the books; and
Avail the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts provided under COA Circular No. 2020-006 relative to the conduct of physical count of PPE, recognition of PPE items found at station, and disposition for non-existing/missing PPE items.

We recommended and the Local Chief Executive (LCE) agreed to require the:
MAO, MTO and the Municipal Engineer’s Office to prepare and submit the necessary reports and records pertaining to local road network in accordance with the prescribed formats as provided under COA Circular No. 2015-008;
MA and the MT to conduct regular reconciliation of LRNLCs and the LRNPCs at least on a quarterly basis;
Municipal Engineer to furnish the MA and the MT with complete description and cost segregation of the various road components for completed road projects as basis for recording;
MA to disclose the total road network in the Notes to the FS as per Annex B of the aforesaid circular; and
MT, with the assistance of the Municipal Engineer, to prepare a report on the footbridge destroyed by typhoon including the Inventory and Inspection Report of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) and furnish the same to the MA as basis to drop from the books of accounts the cost of the destroyed footbridge.  In case a similar report was previously prepared, the same could be used instead.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to require, through the MT:
the collectors to remit promptly their collections to the MT in accordance with the prescribed period of remittance;
the collectors to prepare always the RCD every time they remit their collections to the MT and show the actual date of remittance;
the MT to always put the date of acceptance of the amount remitted by the collectors in the RCD for verification purposes;
the collectors to maintain updated cashbooks to monitor properly their collections and issuance of accountable forms;
the MT to monitor and enforce strictly daily remittance of collections by revenue collectors to avoid accumulation of cash and possible loss thereof through theft or misappropriation; and
the MT to advise the BTs to remit regularly their respective collections due to the MGM.
We also recommended and the LCE agreed to direct:
the MT to deposit all collections intact daily or not later than the next banking day to the AGDB pursuant to the pertinent regulations on the receipts and deposit of government monies;
the MA and the MT to prioritize the reconciliation of the Cash–Local Treasury account to come up with the correct balance thereof;
the MA to present in the Notes to FS the undeposited collections of the current MT and the previous MT to avoid misinterpretation;
Require the previous MTs to turn-over immediately their undeposited collection to the incumbent MT; and
Exhaust all administrative remedies to collect the undeposited collections or resort to legal sanctions, if necessary.

We recommended and the Management agreed to:
Compel the concerned AOs to settle immediately in full or refund their outstanding CAs, either by liquidation, by payment or through salary deductions;
Issue demand letters to all AOs concerned with outstanding CAs including those already separated from service.  Copy of the said demand letters bearing the receipts of the concerned AOs should be furnished to the AT;
Instruct the MA to draw the necessary correcting entries for the negative and/or erroneous balances due for adjustments; and
If warranted after review and evaluation, file a request for authority to write-off dormant unliquidated CAs to COA, duly supported with applicable documents and in accordance with the procedures prescribed in COA Circular No. 2016-005 for CAs of former officials and employees who are already deceased or cannot be located wherein the settlement/collectability of the same is unlikely.  Henceforth, adhere strictly with the governing law, rules and regulations on the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Act diligently in resolving existing issues or problems that are currently hampering the completion of the project;
Allot sufficient fund for the unfinished works of the Mambajog Bridge;
Ensure that regular monitoring and timely and thorough inspection are conducted to avoid further delays in the implementation of the project;
Require the contractor to refund the amount of loss incurred by the MGM due to the contractor’s fault; and
In blacklisting a contractor, follow the “Uniform Guidelines for Blacklisting of Manufacturers, Suppliers, Distributors, Contractors and Consultants” in accordance with Section 69.4 of the Implementing Rules and Regulations (IRR) Part A of RA No. 9184, to prevent/prohibit the erring contractor from further transacting with other government agencies.

We recommended and the Management agreed to require the:
MA to monitor closely the preparation of needed schedules for remittance of withheld taxes and ensure remittance in full within the prescribed deadlines;
MT to remit immediately the amounts withheld to BIR and ensure that monthly payments correspond to the exact amounts withheld to avoid penalties and surcharges; and
MA to facilitate the reconciliation of prior years’ withheld taxes with the amounts remitted to determine the actual amounts due to BIR.  Thereafter, prepare the necessary adjusting entry to correct the Due to BIR account;

We recommended and the Management agreed to require the:
MA to conduct detailed review and analysis of the Inter-Agency Payables accounts, including confirmation and reconciliation with the concerned government agencies to come up with the correct unremitted balances of the payable accounts.  Thereafter, prepare the necessary adjusting entry, if warranted;
MA to monitor closely the preparation of necessary schedules of remittances of withheld amounts and ensure that these are paid in full within the prescribed deadlines;
MT and MA to ensure availability of funds for the immediate remittance of the mandatory contributions and loan amortizations to GSIS, Pag-IBIG and PhilHealth to avoid paying penalties, surcharges and interest arising from delayed remittances; and
Require the liable/accountable officials to settle personally the interest due to GSIS and future penalties and surcharges if determined negligent in the performance of duties.

Instruct the Inventory Committee to complete the physical count of all properties of the Municipality and submit the corresponding RPCPPE within the prescribed period, thereafter be reconciled with the accounting records;

Record the unserviceable property and obsolete PPEs in the Inventory and Inspection Report for Unserviceable Property (IIRUP), if any;

Mobilize additional competent personnel from other departments to assist and facilitate the completion of the physical count of all PPE items;

Hire or designate a GSO who will be in charge in the safekeeping of LGUs assets together with its records;

Strengthen the controls on the handling and recording procedures for the PPE accounts by performing a periodic reconciliation of the records, and ensure that any discrepancies noted are immediately investigated and adjusted in the books accordingly; 

Require the Office of the Municipal Accountant to maintain complete and updated PPELCs to support GL accounts balance and the Supply Officer to keep corresponding PCs for control purposes; and

Consider the provision of COA Circular No. 2020-006 on the conduct of physical count of PPE, recognition of PPE items found at station, and disposition for non-existing/missing PPE items, for the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts balance of the LGU.

We recommended that Management:
Compel the concerned AOs to immediately settle in full or refund their outstanding cash advances, either by liquidation, by payment or through salary deductions;

Require the Municipal Accountant to issue demand letters to concerned AOs with outstanding cash advances including those which were already separated from service. For AOs still in the service, if no actions are render despite the reminders, cause the withholding of the concerned AOs’ salaries and institute legal sanctions as provided for by existing laws and regulations. Also, furnish the Audit Team a copy of the said demand letters bearing the receipts of the concerned accountable officials/employees;

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to draw the necessary correcting entries for the negative and erroneous balances due for adjustments;

Require the Municipal Accountant and concerned department heads to evaluate individually the probability of collection, institute legal sanction/action, if warranted, and consider request for write-off pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016, for the unliquidated cash advances granted to the retired, resign
Strictly adhere with the governing law, rules and regulations on the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Exert effort to trace and analyze the pertinent transactions in order to reconcile the difference of ₱2.71 million in the reciprocal accounts Due from/Due to Other Funds;

Thereafter, prepare the adjusting entries to reflect the correct balances of the subject accounts; 

Ensure that the discrepancy between the reciprocal accounts be immediately eliminated, if not,reduce the balance of said amount in the ensuing year; and

Strictly conduct periodic reconciliation of the reciprocal accounts in order to identify possible errors/adjustments which need to be adjusted in the books.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:

Strictly monitor the conduct of regular and periodic verification, analysis and validation of the existence of receivable and payable accounts to ensure that only valid receivables and payables are recorded in the books;

Prepare a detailed schedule and ageing of receivables and payables once valid supporting documents are retrieved;

Document and file a request for authority to write-off dormant receivable accounts to COA as prescribed by the above cited Circular. Pending approval of such write-off, disclosed the actual account status in the Notes to FS to fairly present the receivable accounts in the FS; and

Prepare a certified schedule of ageing of dormant payable accounts for which there are no valid claimants/creditors and no supporting documents, and thereafter revert the verified amounts to the Unappropriated Surplus of the Government Equity Account by preparing the necessary Journal Entry Vouchers as basis for recording in the books of accounts of the Municipality.

We recommended that the Municipality’s LSB:

Prepare a three-year program indicating strategic prioritization policies in the allocation of the SEF to schools;

Gather and keep records of the information needed to be considered in the planning and budgeting for SEF, particularly the SIP and the information in the CY 2020 allocation for each school from the national budget;

Consolidate the project proposals prepared and submitted by the School Heads for their respective SEF allocation which shall form part of the documentary support for the approval of the SEF Budget;

Ensure that the proposed PPAs presented in the SEF Budget are specifically identified as to name of the project, program and activity, allotment class and recipient school; and

Strictly observe fully the policies in the planning and budgeting for SEF and the procedures and timelines in the preparation and approval of the budget for the said fund as stated in the DepEd, DBM and DILG JC No. 01, series of 2017.

We recommended that Management:

Submit to COA at the beginning of the year, the list of all on-going GPPAs and those that are to be implemented during the year;

Inform the Audit Team within 10 days after the award of the infrastructure project or before it commence, that the appropriate project signboards and/or public notices are already posted; 

Ensure the monthly preparation and submission of the monitoring report on PPAs to the Office of the Auditor; and

Include in the report all the PPAs implemented by the LGU regardless of its amount or source of funds and whether the said PPAs were implemented by contract or otherwise.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Instruct the Inventory Committee to complete the physical count of all properties of the Municipality and submit the corresponding RPCPPE within the prescribed period, thereafter be reconciled with the accounting records;
Record the unserviceable property and obsolete PPEs in the Inventory and Inspection Report for Unserviceable Property (IIRUP), if any;
Mobilize additional competent personnel from other departments to assist and facilitate the completion of the physical count of all PPE items;
Hire or designate a GSO who will be in charge in the safekeeping of LGUs assets together with its records;
Strengthen the controls on the handling and recording procedures for the PPE accounts by performing a periodic reconciliation of the records, and ensure that any discrepancies noted are immediately investigated and adjusted in the books accordingly;
Require the Office of the Municipal Accountant to maintain complete and updated PPELCs to support GL accounts balance and the Supply Officer to keep corresponding PCs for control purposes; and
Consider the provision of COA Circular No. 2020-006 on the conduct of physical count of PPE, recognition of PPE items found at station, and disposition for non-existing/missing PPE items, for the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts balance of the LGU.

We recommended that Management:
Compel the concerned AOs to immediately settle in full or refund their outstanding cash advances, either by liquidation, by payment or through salary deductions;
Require the Municipal Accountant to issue demand letters to concerned AOs with outstanding cash advances including those which were already separated from service. For AOs still in the service, if no actions are rendered despite the reminders, cause the withholding of the concerned AOs’ salaries and institute legal sanctions as provided for by existing laws and regulations. Also, furnish the Audit Team a copy of the said demand letters bearing the receipts of the concerned accountable officials/employees;
Instruct the Municipal Accountant to draw the necessary correcting entries for the negative and erroneous balances due for adjustments;
Require the Municipal Accountant and concerned department heads to evaluate individually the probability of collection, institute legal sanction/action, if warranted, and consider filing a request for write-off pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016, for the unliquidated cash advances granted to the retired, resigned or inactive and deceased employees; and
Strictly adhere with the governing law, rules and regulations on the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances.

We recommended that Management direct the Municipal Accountant to:
Exert effort to trace and analyze the pertinent transactions in order to reconcile the difference of ₱2.71 million in the reciprocal accounts Due from/Due to Other Funds;
Thereafter, prepare the necessary adjusting entries to reflect the correct balances of the subject accounts;
Ensure that the discrepancy between the reciprocal accounts be immediately eliminated, if not, reduce the balance of said amount in the ensuing year; and
Strictly conduct periodic reconciliation of the reciprocal accounts in order to identify possible errors/adjustments which need to be adjusted in the books.

We recommended that Management require the Municipal Accountant to:
Strictly monitor the conduct of regular and periodic verification, analysis and validation of the existence of receivable and payable accounts to ensure that only valid receivables and payables are recorded in the books;
Prepare a detailed schedule and ageing of receivables and payables once valid supporting documents are retrieved;
Document and file a request for authority to write-off dormant receivable accounts to COA as prescribed by the above cited Circular. Pending approval of such write-off, disclosed the actual account status in the Notes to FS to fairly present the receivable accounts in the FS; and
Prepare a certified schedule of ageing of dormant payable accounts for which there are no valid claimants/creditors and no supporting documents, and thereafter revert the verified amounts to the Unappropriated Surplus of the Government Equity Account by preparing the necessary Journal Entry Vouchers as basis for recording in the books of accounts of the Municipality.

We recommended and Management agreed that the Municipality’s LSB:
Prepare a three-year program indicating strategic prioritization policies in the allocation of the SEF to schools;
Gather and keep records of the information needed to be considered in the planning and budgeting for SEF, particularly the SIP and the information in the CY 2020 allocation for each school from the national budget;
Consolidate the project proposals prepared and submitted by the School Heads for their respective SEF allocation which shall form part of the documentary support for the approval of the SEF Budget;
Ensure that the proposed PPAs presented in the SEF Budget are specifically identified as to name of the project, program and activity, allotment class and recipient school; and
