We recommended that the Local Chief Executive require the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to comply with the requirements as provided by RA 9184 specifically the procurement of medicines.

We also recommended that Management require the following documentary requirements in claims for payment of medicines:

The Purchase Request (PR) shall be accompanied by the RHU physician certification that medicines and drugs requisitioned is contained in the Philippine Drug Formulary, Vol. I current edition pursuant to E.O. No. 49 dated January 29, 1999 in order to ensure that medicines and drugs procured and dispensed by the LGU is compliant with the Generic Act of 1988;

Antibiotics be supported with Batch Certificate pursuant to RA 3720 as amended by E.O. No. 175 dated May 22, 1987. Inits absence, test analysis by BFAD be resorted to ensure its safety, efficacy and good quality;

The winning bidder’s LTO is authentic and valid and that the individual manufacturer or local distributor in case of foreign drugs as appearing in the CPR of every medicine delivered reconciles with the List of Sources in the LTO to ensure that the supplier is an authorized wholesaler or distributor;

Sales Invoice or Delivery Receipt (SI or DR) shall contain the Lot Number and Expiry Date of the medicines procured and delivered as basis of the determination of the six months required expiry date after the delivery; and

License to Operate (LTO), Certificate of Good Manufacturing Practice (CGMP) and Certificate of Product Registration (CPR) shall be attached in every claim and shall be authenticated by the BAC Secretariat based on the originals presented in order to ensure regularity and validity of the documents.

